OF THE Ps1TAcUs. psitacus, in English a popinjay, in German eyn papegay.

ARISTOTLE.

An Indian bird indeed, the Psitace by name, which people say can speak, is such a one as this, and is reported as more talkative after it has drunk wine.

PLINY.

Beyond all Psitaci repeat men's wordS, and even talk connectedly. India sends this bird, which they call Psitace‚ with the whole body green marked only by a scarlet ring upon the nape. It will pronounce “Hail Emperor,’' and any words it hears; it is especially sportive after wine. The hardness of the head is the same as of the beak. And when the bird is being taught to speak, it is beaten with an iron rod, else it feels not the strokes. When it flies down it receives its weight upon its beak, and supports itself thereon; and thus lightens itself to remedy the weakness of its feet.

ARISTOTLE.

The Platea, a river bird, devours biggish shell- fish, if they be but smooth, and, after it has seethed them in its crop, it casts them up again, that stripping them off from their gaping shells, it so may pick and eat them.
